phy on the ways minorities and sex workers were marked as the principle carriers of HIV, often despite evidence to the contrary.Hyde approaches HIV/AIDS as a study of the conceptualization and the circulation of a disease across boundaries that requires different kinds of anthropological thinking and methods. She focuses on "everyday AIDS practices" to examine the links between the material and the discursive representations of HIV/AIDS. This book illustrates how representatives of the Chinese government singled out a former kingdom of Thailand, Sipsongpanna, and its indigenous ethnic group, the Tai-Lüe, as carriers of HIV due to a history of prejudice and stigma, and to the geography of the borderlands. Hyde poses questions about the cultural politics of epidemics, state-society relations, Han and non-Han ethnic dynamics, and the rise of an AIDS public health bureaucracy in the post-reform era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAIDS (Disease)xGovernment policyzChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)zChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aProstitution. 0aSocial change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aaids epidemic.  aanthropologists.  achinese culture.  achinese government.  achinese society.  acultural anthropology.  acultural politics.  aethnic discrimination.  aethnic dynamics.  aethnographers.  aethnographic study.  ahan.  ahistory of prejudice.  ahiv aids.  ainfectious diseases.  aminority experience.  apost reform era.  apublic health crisis.  apublic health policies.  asex workers.  asocial historians.  asocial stigmas.  asouthwest china.  athailand.  ayunnan province.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 200